00:50:21.294 --> 00:50:24.000
AUDIENCE: The follow-up to
that question-- and this

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.198
may seem very uninformed,
but I'll ask it anyway.

00:50:27.198 --> 00:50:31.134
So let's say you do have
a village that flees

00:50:31.134 --> 00:50:33.594
and lands in another country.

00:50:33.594 --> 00:50:38.145
Do people just continue on their
professions within the camps?

00:50:38.145 --> 00:50:41.466
So for example, if there were
teachers in that village,

00:50:41.466 --> 00:50:44.910
can they continue or is
there not enough organized--

00:50:44.910 --> 00:50:50.234
does the camp organize itself
as it may have been in the past?

00:50:50.234 --> 00:50:51.900
BEN RAWLENCE: Yeah,
there's definitely--

00:50:51.900 --> 00:50:53.441
the question was
about whether people

00:50:53.441 --> 00:50:55.640
continue their old
professions in the camp,

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:57.060
once they move there.

00:50:57.060 --> 00:50:59.240
There's definitely
an element of that.

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:02.380
But often, you
can't always find--

00:51:02.380 --> 00:51:05.116
there isn't the job to do.

00:51:05.116 --> 00:51:09.779
But there certainly is an
element of self-organizing.

00:51:09.779 --> 00:51:11.820
What would be great would
be if the refugees were

00:51:11.820 --> 00:51:15.150
empowered more to organize
themselves and to run things,

00:51:15.150 --> 00:51:17.470
and given the proper support,
and the proper budget,

00:51:17.470 --> 00:51:20.150
and the equipment, and so on.

00:51:20.150 --> 00:51:22.960
For example, there's a
community police force.

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:24.720
What they want
more than anything

00:51:24.720 --> 00:51:28.670
is boots, because you can't get
good shoes in a refugee camp.

00:51:28.670 --> 00:51:32.010
Everybody is either
barefoot or in flip flops.

00:51:32.010 --> 00:51:34.930
And the other thing they
want is two-way radios.

00:51:34.930 --> 00:51:37.750
Because they're all using
their own mobile phones.

00:51:37.750 --> 00:51:40.030
And they get given a
little bit of phone credit,

00:51:40.030 --> 00:51:43.240
like scratch cards, to
top up their phones.

00:51:43.240 --> 00:51:47.009
But often that's not enough,
or it runs out, or whatever.

00:51:47.009 --> 00:51:49.550
What they want is two-way radios
so that they can communicate

00:51:49.550 --> 00:51:51.460
about their patrolling.

00:51:51.460 --> 00:51:52.772
They don't have weapons.

00:51:52.772 --> 00:51:54.730
But if there's a problem,
they call the police.

00:51:54.730 --> 00:51:56.271
But in order to call
the police, they

00:51:56.271 --> 00:51:59.610
have to have a cell
phone with credit on it.

00:51:59.610 --> 00:52:02.490
So there's tiny things like
that that if you supported them

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:04.844
properly and allowed them
to do their own thing,

00:52:04.844 --> 00:52:06.510
they could make the
camp a better place.

